caption.text:
ZEPPELIN TAKE NEW YORK - 49 years since Led Zeppelin blew the doors off of New Yorkâ€™s Madison Square Garden. Here, the band can be seen in the midst of of â€œDazed and Confusedâ€ with Jimmy Page playing a cool little start/stop section that the fans are surely appreciating. Zeppelin came out with such a high-level of energy for these shows and itâ€™s pretty remarkable for a band that was just wrapping up a massive two-leg tour. They performed for three straight nights at MSG, which were professionally filmed for the concert film â€œThe Song Remains The Same.â€ 

1973 was a big year for Zeppelin. Just 2 months prior to these New York shows, they played to 56,800 fans in Tampa, breaking The Beatles record for an audience set at Shea Stadium in 1965. At this point, it really seemed like Zeppelin had few battles they hadnâ€™t won. To Jimmy Page, the lead guitarist and architect of the band, it was Zepâ€™s time to shine. â€œBy 1973 we really had confidence,â€ Page told Brad Tolinski in Light and Shade (2013). â€œBy then we were not only able to play but also project with it.â€ With the huge momentum the band was riding, Page got caught up in this and didnâ€™t sleep for FIVE nights during these MSG shows. Page tried to break down what it was like leaving an arena full of adrenaline like he was in New York at the end of that â€™73 tour. He said he couldnâ€™t have slept if he tried. So he basically stopped trying. â€œWe were in New York, we were making a movie and playing great shows,â€ Page said. â€œIt was difficult to shut down that kind of electricity. Youâ€™d try to go to bed, but most of the time you gave up, because it was more fun to go out and enjoy yourself.â€ Enjoy
